Authorities need
to decide, are you

00:25:59.360 --> 00:26:04.460
going to isolate this world,
regulate it, integrate it?

00:26:04.460 --> 00:26:06.510
Now, some countries--
I don't think anybody's

00:26:06.510 --> 00:26:07.800
fully isolated it.

00:26:07.800 --> 00:26:09.330
But some countries,
in a sense, have

00:26:09.330 --> 00:26:12.210
said, let's ban a
lot of this activity.

00:26:12.210 --> 00:26:14.043
And Kelly?

00:26:14.043 --> 00:26:15.460
AUDIENCE: Can I
ask to what extent

00:26:15.460 --> 00:26:17.740
are other countries looking
to comments like this

00:26:17.740 --> 00:26:21.353
to decide what stance
they're going to take?

00:26:21.353 --> 00:26:22.770
GARY GENSLER:
Kelly's question is,

00:26:22.770 --> 00:26:26.220
so to what extent to comments
from a Mark Carney who's

00:26:26.220 --> 00:26:28.128
the governor of the
Bank of England,

00:26:28.128 --> 00:26:30.420
but heads the Financial
Stability Board-- how much does

00:26:30.420 --> 00:26:35.670
that influence the rest of
the official sector community?

00:26:35.670 --> 00:26:36.880
And it's a great question.

00:26:36.880 --> 00:26:39.030
I think that it all
goes into the mix.

00:26:39.030 --> 00:26:46.620
I think that there's probably
in any public policy sphere

00:26:46.620 --> 00:26:51.030
six to a dozen
countries that really

00:26:51.030 --> 00:26:57.120
take the lead, not legally.

00:26:57.120 --> 00:26:58.620
They're not taking
the lead legally,

00:26:58.620 --> 00:27:01.110
they're just taking
the lead because others

00:27:01.110 --> 00:27:07.090
follow that which is said in the
US, the European Union, China,

00:27:07.090 --> 00:27:08.010
Japan.

00:27:08.010 --> 00:27:13.050
I mean, we know the usual
and the normal countries.

00:27:13.050 --> 00:27:17.010
But part of it is because
the depth and breadth

00:27:17.010 --> 00:27:21.730
of their economies,
part of it in this world

00:27:21.730 --> 00:27:24.370
the depth and breadth of
their financial markets.

00:27:24.370 --> 00:27:27.130
But it's also because
often their opinion

00:27:27.130 --> 00:27:31.720
leaders and their opinions
are somewhat respected.

00:27:31.720 --> 00:27:34.600
But we have 180
or 190 countries.

00:27:34.600 --> 00:27:37.030
And each one of them
has a different culture,

00:27:37.030 --> 00:27:39.130
and each has a different
political system,

00:27:39.130 --> 00:27:43.690
and a different history, and
different economic well-being.

00:27:43.690 --> 00:27:48.760
So I went into the international
arena doing regulation thinking

00:27:48.760 --> 00:27:53.890
it would it is a dystopian
view that there's

00:27:53.890 --> 00:27:58.540
going to be one worldwide regime
for almost any public policy

00:27:58.540 --> 00:28:01.120
issue.

00:28:01.120 --> 00:28:04.790
I mean, I don't know if it
exists in almost any place.

00:28:04.790 --> 00:28:06.880
But when you get to
financial services,

00:28:06.880 --> 00:28:10.690
it's pretty unlikely because
of all those different cultures

00:28:10.690 --> 00:28:14.260
and histories and political
systems and economies

00:28:14.260 --> 00:28:15.680
clashing up against each other.

00:28:15.680 --> 00:28:16.310
Yes?

00:28:16.310 --> 00:28:18.560
AUDIENCE: I was just wondering
if you can explain more

00:28:18.560 --> 00:28:22.480
about what you mean by
China leading the effort--

00:28:22.480 --> 00:28:23.620
GARY GENSLER: China's--

00:28:23.620 --> 00:28:26.800
AUDIENCE: Is leading the effort
in regulating the blockchain,

00:28:26.800 --> 00:28:30.130
because China has banned
the exchange of Fiat

00:28:30.130 --> 00:28:31.550
money [INAUDIBLE].

00:28:31.550 --> 00:28:34.400
GARY GENSLER: So the
question is China.

00:28:34.400 --> 00:28:40.930
So how many in the room think
China would be in the isolate--

00:28:40.930 --> 00:28:43.540
dominantly in the isolate
category rather than

00:28:43.540 --> 00:28:47.350
the integrate category?

00:28:47.350 --> 00:28:49.170
So a quarter or a third.

00:28:49.170 --> 00:28:49.890
It's interesting.

00:28:49.890 --> 00:28:50.970
It's really a hybrid.

00:28:50.970 --> 00:28:56.800
China came pretty strongly
saying no to a lot of activity.

00:28:56.800 --> 00:29:00.390
And yet, two of the biggest
mining poles for Bitcoin

00:29:00.390 --> 00:29:02.430
are in China.

00:29:02.430 --> 00:29:05.340
Some of the crypto
exchanges left China,

00:29:05.340 --> 00:29:09.180
but those miners are the
biggest sellers of Bitcoin,

00:29:09.180 --> 00:29:10.890
because they're
collecting the Bitcoin

00:29:10.890 --> 00:29:14.790
and need to sell them, have
to find some crypto exchange

00:29:14.790 --> 00:29:18.390
somewhere that is
no longer in China.

00:29:18.390 --> 00:29:20.610
I'm going to mispronounce
the name of the exchange.

00:29:20.610 --> 00:29:28.320
But Huobi, H-U-O-B-I, is still
very much a Chinese crypto

00:29:28.320 --> 00:29:29.160
exchange.

00:29:29.160 --> 00:29:31.980
I think it's now
registered in Malta

00:29:31.980 --> 00:29:34.940
if I'm not mistaken maybe.

00:29:34.940 --> 00:29:39.390
So there's a love-hate hybrid.

00:29:39.390 --> 00:29:43.680
The Central Bank of China
has very active projects

00:29:43.680 --> 00:29:46.620
with regard to
blockchain technology.

00:29:46.620 --> 00:29:50.290
And they have a whole
lab and it's public.

00:29:50.290 --> 00:29:52.170
That which is public is public.

00:29:52.170 --> 00:29:54.150
That which is private
probably is bigger

00:29:54.150 --> 00:29:55.960
and we just don't know about it.

00:29:55.960 --> 00:30:01.560
So there's a bit of a mixed
approach even in China,

00:30:01.560 --> 00:30:05.370
if that answers your question.

00:30:05.370 --> 00:30:07.770
So let me just go--

00:30:07.770 --> 00:30:10.200
I've spent a lot of time
in the last six months

00:30:10.200 --> 00:30:11.850
traveling around the
globe and speaking

00:30:11.850 --> 00:30:17.760
at different conferences, OECD,
in Japan, and here in the US.

00:30:17.760 --> 00:30:20.940
What I see-- guarding
against illicit activity,

00:30:20.940 --> 00:30:22.470
broad consensus.

00:30:22.470 --> 00:30:26.190
180-190 countries, yeah,
we've got to do it.

00:30:26.190 --> 00:30:30.560
Really choppy performance
on implementation,

00:30:30.560 --> 00:30:34.310
and sometimes a little bit of a
head fake from one jurisdiction

00:30:34.310 --> 00:30:36.080
to another, because
some actually

00:30:36.080 --> 00:30:38.690
are fine with tax
evasion as long as it's

00:30:38.690 --> 00:30:43.090
tax evasion in the other
person's jurisdiction.

00:30:43.090 --> 00:30:46.270
Usually, low
population centers are

00:30:46.270 --> 00:30:49.720
more comfortable promoting
being tax havens,

00:30:49.720 --> 00:30:53.480
trying to take economic
activity from elsewhere.

00:30:53.480 --> 00:30:55.720
But there's general
broad consensus

00:30:55.720 --> 00:30:58.390
and it's usually centered
on finance ministries

00:30:58.390 --> 00:31:01.690
and central bank authorities
and the equivalent

00:31:01.690 --> 00:31:04.930
of law enforcement,
our Justice Department.

00:31:04.930 --> 00:31:05.650
Think of those.

00:31:05.650 --> 00:31:09.930
That's where the nexus is
happening country by country.

00:31:09.930 --> 00:31:14.100
Financial stability, general
consensus to monitor--

00:31:14.100 --> 00:31:17.130
there's not a deep
worry right now,

00:31:17.130 --> 00:31:21.270
because the space is only a
quarter of a trillion dollars.

00:31:21.270 --> 00:31:23.880
And the worldwide
capital markets--

00:31:23.880 --> 00:31:26.820
the worldwide debt
markets are $250 trillion,

00:31:26.820 --> 00:31:29.760
nearly 1,000 times bigger.

00:31:29.760 --> 00:31:33.960
And the worldwide equity
markets are about $90 trillion.

00:31:33.960 --> 00:31:38.700
And even the worldwide stock
of gold, at $7 trillion,

00:31:38.700 --> 00:31:42.450
is nearly 30 times as large.

00:31:42.450 --> 00:31:48.540
It just gives you a sense of
the relationship right now why

00:31:48.540 --> 00:31:53.790
let's monitor, but it's probably
not systemic destabilizing.

00:31:53.790 --> 00:31:55.860
However, there's
different perspectives,

00:31:55.860 --> 00:31:58.920
particularly in countries
that have capital controls,

00:31:58.920 --> 00:32:02.400
because it could be
destabilizing to a currency

00:32:02.400 --> 00:32:03.720
in that way.

00:32:03.720 --> 00:32:05.940
And then thirdly, the
investing public--

00:32:05.940 --> 00:32:07.470
protecting investing
public, I would

00:32:07.470 --> 00:32:10.050
say the views are wide ranging.

00:32:10.050 --> 00:32:12.720
In the US and
Canada, more forward

00:32:12.720 --> 00:32:16.560
leaning, more a
lot of this stuff--

00:32:16.560 --> 00:32:18.900
maybe these initial
coin offerings

00:32:18.900 --> 00:32:23.340
are securities that
need to be protected.

00:32:23.340 --> 00:32:24.960
And in a bunch of
other countries,

00:32:24.960 --> 00:32:28.590
it's like let 1,000
flowers bloom.

00:32:28.590 --> 00:32:30.960
Let's promote
innovation and so forth.

00:32:30.960 --> 00:32:34.470
And it's a pretty wide view.

00:32:34.470 --> 00:32:37.860
My personal view is, and I've
said this at some conferences,

00:32:37.860 --> 00:32:48.020
if this grew from a quarter of
a to five and 10 and 20 times

00:32:48.020 --> 00:32:52.070
the size, or if the ICO
marketplace, which has raised

00:32:52.070 --> 00:32:57.130
about $20 to $25 billion
today, kept raising that

00:32:57.130 --> 00:33:00.140
but went to like $100
billion a year raise,

00:33:00.140 --> 00:33:01.860
then a bunch of
countries would probably

00:33:01.860 --> 00:33:04.020
want more investor protection.

00:33:04.020 --> 00:33:07.330
I think-- this is just
my personal view--

00:33:07.330 --> 00:33:11.970
we will never have uniform
jurisdiction, uniform laws.

00:33:11.970 --> 00:33:14.610
But part of what's going
on is this is so new

00:33:14.610 --> 00:33:19.150
and it's still relatively small
versus the capital markets.

00:33:19.150 --> 00:33:22.110
If it grew, I think
more countries

00:33:22.110 --> 00:33:24.633
would want some protection.

00:33:24.633 --> 00:33:27.050
AUDIENCE: I have a question
regarding the illicit equities

00:33:27.050 --> 00:33:28.505
and financial stability.

00:33:28.505 --> 00:33:29.880
As you traveled
to other country,

00:33:29.880 --> 00:33:34.050
what metrics were they using
to measure their success

00:33:34.050 --> 00:33:36.215
or monitor on those fronts?

00:33:36.215 --> 00:33:38.340
GARY GENSLER: So the question
is what are countries

00:33:38.340 --> 00:33:40.377
doing to measure for success.

00:33:40.377 --> 00:33:42.210
I'm going to use one
example, and then we'll

00:33:42.210 --> 00:33:44.220
keep going into the details.

00:33:44.220 --> 00:33:49.350
Japan had some of the
earliest crypto exchanges, Mt.

00:33:49.350 --> 00:33:51.660
Gox, G-O-X. Mt.

00:33:51.660 --> 00:33:56.190
Gox was an early exchange
that the promoters, the owners

00:33:56.190 --> 00:34:01.080
moved to Tokyo, even though
they weren't Japanese nationals.

00:34:01.080 --> 00:34:04.530
So it was it was
centered in Tokyo.

00:34:04.530 --> 00:34:08.760
And it went down when about
half a billion dollars of value

00:34:08.760 --> 00:34:09.960
was lost.

00:34:09.960 --> 00:34:14.460
It was supposedly a
hack, stolen crypto.

00:34:14.460 --> 00:34:16.480
It was aan interesting case.

00:34:16.480 --> 00:34:18.929
It was actually being
stolen over many months.

00:34:18.929 --> 00:34:21.480
It wasn't one specific hack.

00:34:21.480 --> 00:34:27.659
So Japan in 2017 finally got
around and changed their laws.

00:34:27.659 --> 00:34:33.100
And they put in a whole regime
to regulate crypto exchanges,

00:34:33.100 --> 00:34:37.530
particularly around this
customer protection custody

00:34:37.530 --> 00:34:40.139
issue and around
illicit activity.

00:34:40.139 --> 00:34:43.020
And they actually have
gone in and asked exchanges

00:34:43.020 --> 00:34:44.250
to register.

00:34:44.250 --> 00:34:49.350
They go in and actually
do examinations.

00:34:49.350 --> 00:34:51.540
And earlier this
year, of the, I think,

00:34:51.540 --> 00:34:54.449
30 some registered
exchanges, five

00:34:54.449 --> 00:34:57.780
or 10 had to cease operations.

00:34:57.780 --> 00:35:01.420
How do they measure
success or failure?

00:35:01.420 --> 00:35:03.630
Another exchange in
January of this year

00:35:03.630 --> 00:35:07.770
lost another half a
billion dollars to a hack.

00:35:07.770 --> 00:35:12.030
Their principal executive,
their prime minister,

00:35:12.030 --> 00:35:14.340
got a question in
a news conference.

00:35:14.340 --> 00:35:18.670
If you're a regulator,
that's not a good thing.

00:35:18.670 --> 00:35:22.980
So sometimes, you measure
success or failure

00:35:22.980 --> 00:35:28.440
as to whether your boss gets a
question in a news conference

00:35:28.440 --> 00:35:30.390
about why it's not working.

00:35:30.390 --> 00:35:32.760
The Japanese have been
terrific, by the way,

00:35:32.760 --> 00:35:35.110
in terms of what they're doing.

00:35:35.110 --> 00:35:38.400
But I'm just using that as
an example of sometimes.

00:35:40.980 --> 00:35:44.060
So let me just chat about a
deep dive into each of these

00:35:44.060 --> 00:35:46.800
in probably five
or 10 minutes each,

00:35:46.800 --> 00:35:49.800
which you could do a whole
course on each of these.

00:35:49.800 --> 00:35:51.990
But let me just deep
dive a little bit.

00:35:51.990 --> 00:35:55.590
Guarding against
illicit activity--

00:35:55.590 --> 00:35:59.550
so tax compliance and
reporting, what do you

00:35:59.550 --> 00:36:02.100
think the first big question
that the US government

00:36:02.100 --> 00:36:04.980
or any government--
this sounds US-centric.

00:36:04.980 --> 00:36:06.750
And Kelly, I thank
you for your paper,

00:36:06.750 --> 00:36:08.925
because Kelly-- is
it all right if I

00:36:08.925 --> 00:36:11.175
call you out-- wrote a paper
for today, which I happen

00:36:11.175 --> 00:36:14.400
to read earlier today and
said Gensler's work was

00:36:14.400 --> 00:36:15.345
too US-centric.

00:36:17.657 --> 00:36:18.615
I thought it was gutsy.

00:36:18.615 --> 00:36:19.760
I thought it was gutsy.

00:36:19.760 --> 00:36:20.580
But you're right.

00:36:20.580 --> 00:36:21.780
It was US-centric.

00:36:21.780 --> 00:36:25.050
I was speaking to
the US Congress.

00:36:25.050 --> 00:36:27.270
So that was this thing you
learn in politics, too.

00:36:27.270 --> 00:36:29.780
You try to gauge your audience.

00:36:29.780 --> 00:36:31.230
But you were right.

00:36:31.230 --> 00:36:33.330
But what do you
think the first thing

00:36:33.330 --> 00:36:35.600
whether it's the US government
or any government's got

00:36:35.600 --> 00:36:40.800
to figure out in terms of this
world came along in 2010, 2011,

00:36:40.800 --> 00:36:44.910
2012-- what was that
first question, which

00:36:44.910 --> 00:36:46.740
you may have teased
out of the readings,

00:36:46.740 --> 00:36:49.670
but as a policy question?

00:36:49.670 --> 00:36:53.610
Anybody want to take a guess?

00:36:53.610 --> 00:36:56.505
AUDIENCE: How do you
treat it for tax purposes?

00:36:56.505 --> 00:36:58.630
GARY GENSLER: How do you
treat it for tax purposes?

00:36:58.630 --> 00:37:04.130
How do you treat Bitcoin at
the time for tax purposes?

00:37:04.130 --> 00:37:06.620
And so that central
question was the first thing

00:37:06.620 --> 00:37:08.060
that really came up.

00:37:08.060 --> 00:37:09.170
Is it a currency?

00:37:09.170 --> 00:37:10.640
Is it a form of property?

00:37:10.640 --> 00:37:12.350
Is it something else?

00:37:12.350 --> 00:37:16.460
What did the US government say
back in, I think it was 2013?

00:37:16.460 --> 00:37:19.580
But it would it be
in the testimony.

00:37:19.580 --> 00:37:20.090
What is it?

00:37:20.090 --> 00:37:22.130
Is it a currency or property?

00:37:22.130 --> 00:37:22.940
AUDIENCE: Property.

00:37:22.940 --> 00:37:23.720
GARY GENSLER: Property.

00:37:23.720 --> 00:37:25.137
AUDIENCE: It makes
for a pain when

00:37:25.137 --> 00:37:27.740
you're filling out your taxes
and you do any sort of trading.

00:37:27.740 --> 00:37:28.865
GARY GENSLER: That's right.

00:37:28.865 --> 00:37:31.453
So the result of that is--
you want to say it again?

00:37:31.453 --> 00:37:32.870
AUDIENCE: You have
to-- basically,

00:37:32.870 --> 00:37:36.140
every time you exchange
to another currency

00:37:36.140 --> 00:37:40.660
or you spend it, you have
to record the cost basis.

00:37:40.660 --> 00:37:43.240
And yeah, if you do any
sort of my tax return,

00:37:43.240 --> 00:37:44.860
was 600 pages this year.

00:37:44.860 --> 00:37:46.940
it's pretty brutal.

00:37:46.940 --> 00:37:50.690
So any time it changes at
all, you can't consolidate--

00:37:50.690 --> 00:37:53.360
I think it's like with
stocks you can consolidate.

00:37:53.360 --> 00:37:55.820
If it's the same security
being traded over the year,

00:37:55.820 --> 00:37:59.390
you can consolidate to show
your beginning and ending

00:37:59.390 --> 00:38:01.050
and just pay tax on the delta.

00:38:01.050 --> 00:38:03.952
But you have to report
every single trade.

00:38:03.952 --> 00:38:05.660
GARY GENSLER: So these
types of questions

00:38:05.660 --> 00:38:08.900
were not known in 2008
when Satoshi Nakamoto wrote

00:38:08.900 --> 00:38:09.440
his paper.

00:38:09.440 --> 00:38:13.550
But 10 years later, is it
currency, is it property?

00:38:13.550 --> 00:38:17.300
Some jurisdictions around
the globe, very few but some,

00:38:17.300 --> 00:38:20.040
have said its currency.

00:38:20.040 --> 00:38:22.840
But almost dominantly
around the globe,

00:38:22.840 --> 00:38:26.340
it's some form of property,
and then within the laws

00:38:26.340 --> 00:38:27.990
triggers, like it
does in the US,

00:38:27.990 --> 00:38:31.210
capital gains and
so forth like that.

00:38:31.210 --> 00:38:34.000
The next quote set
of questions was,

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:38.110
what's the tax treatment of
mining, exchanges, and forks?

00:38:38.110 --> 00:38:40.120
Anybody want to tell me--

00:38:40.120 --> 00:38:45.580
if you're mining and you receive
Bitcoin or any other crypto,

00:38:45.580 --> 00:38:50.290
Ether, and so forth--

00:38:50.290 --> 00:38:52.130
anybody want to take a guess?

00:38:52.130 --> 00:38:53.070
It's not a guess.

00:38:53.070 --> 00:38:55.660
I think it was even in
the testimony I wrote.

00:38:55.660 --> 00:38:57.455
You had 600 pages.

00:38:57.455 --> 00:38:58.955
AUDIENCE: I know
with a fork anyway,

00:38:58.955 --> 00:39:00.780
you basically pay tax
on the whole thing.

00:39:00.780 --> 00:39:06.040
So a Bitcoin cash fork,
basically the cost basis

00:39:06.040 --> 00:39:09.650
is zero, and whatever its
value at the time you sell it.

00:39:09.650 --> 00:39:11.650
GARY GENSLER: You're
saying you had to pay taxes

00:39:11.650 --> 00:39:13.190
on both sides of the fork?

00:39:13.190 --> 00:39:13.930
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:39:13.930 --> 00:39:16.540
GARY GENSLER: So that's
rougher than a stock split.

00:39:16.540 --> 00:39:19.360
A stock split, you
just carryover basis.

00:39:19.360 --> 00:39:20.610
How about Bitcoin mining?

00:39:20.610 --> 00:39:21.110
Anybody?

00:39:21.110 --> 00:39:22.722
Zan, you want to take it?

00:39:22.722 --> 00:39:24.430
AUDIENCE: I actually
don't know this one,

00:39:24.430 --> 00:39:27.235
but I would assume they
treat it like income.

00:39:27.235 --> 00:39:28.110
GARY GENSLER: Income.

00:39:28.110 --> 00:39:28.960
Zan's right.

00:39:28.960 --> 00:39:30.160
It's income.

00:39:30.160 --> 00:39:32.620
You mine, you get income.

00:39:32.620 --> 00:39:37.660
So each of these had to be
addressed in the tax law.

00:39:37.660 --> 00:39:40.140
The next thing is something
