just skip this slide.

00:53:42.510 --> 00:53:46.280
But here are some of the
concerns around central bank

00:53:46.280 --> 00:53:47.820
digital currencies.

00:53:47.820 --> 00:53:49.880
It could be pro cyclical.

00:53:49.880 --> 00:53:51.920
A central bank
digital currency means

00:53:51.920 --> 00:53:57.180
the central bank
says Joaquin does not

00:53:57.180 --> 00:53:59.730
have to deposit at a
bank to have US dollars.

00:53:59.730 --> 00:54:03.580
He can deposit straight
with the Federal Reserve.

00:54:03.580 --> 00:54:06.010
Or in Sweden, it's
close enough to do it.

00:54:06.010 --> 00:54:09.310
You can deposit straight with
the Swedish central bank.

00:54:09.310 --> 00:54:11.450
We'll talk about this
more in a couple of weeks.

00:54:11.450 --> 00:54:15.670
But that could lead to runs
away from commercial banks

00:54:15.670 --> 00:54:16.890
to central banks.

00:54:16.890 --> 00:54:20.680
AUDIENCE: I think my key
question is, if you do so,

00:54:20.680 --> 00:54:24.280
you run the central bank
digital currency on parallel

00:54:24.280 --> 00:54:25.730
to its Fiat currency.

00:54:25.730 --> 00:54:28.120
And that would
jeopardize the ability

00:54:28.120 --> 00:54:30.550
that the central bank
would be able to carry out

00:54:30.550 --> 00:54:34.280
monetary policy, especially
if you use Bitcoin in a way

00:54:34.280 --> 00:54:39.010
that the supply is rigid, the
ability for you to actually

00:54:39.010 --> 00:54:44.580
carry out for the
likes of [INAUDIBLE]??

00:54:44.580 --> 00:54:46.630
GARY GENSLER: Remind
me your first name?

00:54:46.630 --> 00:54:47.380
Sean.

00:54:47.380 --> 00:54:49.810
So Sean, I agree with Sean.

00:54:49.810 --> 00:54:51.392
Can you hold that
for about two weeks

00:54:51.392 --> 00:54:52.600
when we're going to go deep--

00:54:52.600 --> 00:54:56.840
we're going to do a deep
dive on all of these.

00:54:56.840 --> 00:55:00.820
But basically, Sean's point
is if a central bank issues

00:55:00.820 --> 00:55:03.700
currency directly to
the public digitally,

00:55:03.700 --> 00:55:07.610
could it also undermine
monetary policy?

00:55:07.610 --> 00:55:10.840
And there's a bunch of
neat trade-offs there.

00:55:10.840 --> 00:55:12.520
I leave it for you
just to say we're

00:55:12.520 --> 00:55:14.650
going to come back to that.

00:55:14.650 --> 00:55:17.620
The investing public--
so we've talked

00:55:17.620 --> 00:55:21.710
about that the markets are
readily susceptible to fraud

00:55:21.710 --> 00:55:22.540
manipulation.

00:55:22.540 --> 00:55:24.740
And we're going to spend
a couple of lectures

00:55:24.740 --> 00:55:28.410
on crypto exchanges.

00:55:28.410 --> 00:55:33.310
But they're not regulated
for market integrity.

00:55:33.310 --> 00:55:35.800
So a simple thing like--

00:55:35.800 --> 00:55:37.095
remind me your first name.

00:55:37.095 --> 00:55:38.020
AUDIENCE: Michael.

00:55:38.020 --> 00:55:38.937
GARY GENSLER: Michael.

00:55:38.937 --> 00:55:40.420
Michael has trades.

00:55:40.420 --> 00:55:43.000
And I'm assuming some of
those are on crypto exchanges?

00:55:43.000 --> 00:55:43.770
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:55:43.770 --> 00:55:44.770
GARY GENSLER: All right.

00:55:44.770 --> 00:55:48.010
So when Michael puts an
order on a crypto exchange,

00:55:48.010 --> 00:55:51.670
there's currently no
rules in the rule books,

00:55:51.670 --> 00:55:55.270
no law in the law that
says that exchange

00:55:55.270 --> 00:55:56.980
can't front-run Michael.

00:55:56.980 --> 00:56:01.840
So Michael says he wants
to buy Bitcoin at $6,400

00:56:01.840 --> 00:56:05.620
and the crypto exchange could
buy some in front of him

00:56:05.620 --> 00:56:07.680
at $6,490--

00:56:07.680 --> 00:56:09.790
or $6,390.

00:56:09.790 --> 00:56:11.830
Yeah, sorry.

00:56:11.830 --> 00:56:13.790
That's called front running.

00:56:13.790 --> 00:56:17.260
So there are many,
many ways to make money

00:56:17.260 --> 00:56:22.440
on Michael's order that
can just be goofed around.

00:56:22.440 --> 00:56:24.630
Kyle, is that a question?

00:56:24.630 --> 00:56:28.020
AUDIENCE: I thought that
front-running [INAUDIBLE]

00:56:28.020 --> 00:56:30.480
were criminal activities
if they weren't

00:56:30.480 --> 00:56:35.740
covered in a particular
law or regulation by FINRA.

00:56:35.740 --> 00:56:37.410
Is that not correct?

00:56:37.410 --> 00:56:38.880
GARY GENSLER: So
Kyle is raising--

00:56:38.880 --> 00:56:42.780
well, maybe if it's not covered
by investor protection laws,

00:56:42.780 --> 00:56:45.120
might it be covered
by other laws?

00:56:45.120 --> 00:56:46.740
You mentioned FINRA.

00:56:46.740 --> 00:56:49.980
FINRA, which is the
self-regulatory organization

00:56:49.980 --> 00:56:53.460
in the US for investments,
would be investment law.

00:56:53.460 --> 00:56:54.910
But Kyle, you're right.

00:56:54.910 --> 00:57:00.060
Certain things are still
against consumer laws.

00:57:00.060 --> 00:57:02.490
I don't think front-running
is one of them,

00:57:02.490 --> 00:57:05.630
but you might be
right about that.

00:57:05.630 --> 00:57:07.195
I would contend--

00:57:07.195 --> 00:57:12.110
I'm an advocate that
Western societies early on

00:57:12.110 --> 00:57:14.390
and many developing
countries in Asia,

00:57:14.390 --> 00:57:18.380
elsewhere benefited by
layering investor protection

00:57:18.380 --> 00:57:20.540
over consumer protection.

00:57:20.540 --> 00:57:24.770
That consumer protection is
about transacting and the fraud

00:57:24.770 --> 00:57:27.530
that can happen in a
transaction-- selling

00:57:27.530 --> 00:57:30.080
an automobile,
selling a baby's crib,

00:57:30.080 --> 00:57:33.620
and so forth, selling
a bottle of milk.

00:57:33.620 --> 00:57:38.090
Investor protection also layers
on something else which has

00:57:38.090 --> 00:57:41.690
to do with issuers having
information asymmetries,

00:57:41.690 --> 00:57:43.760
that the issuer
knows something--

00:57:43.760 --> 00:57:45.800
the person raising money--

00:57:45.800 --> 00:57:48.690
and the purchaser does
not know that information.

00:57:48.690 --> 00:57:51.740
There's a lot of
information asymmetries

00:57:51.740 --> 00:57:55.220
that you're trying to
address in the market.

00:57:55.220 --> 00:57:58.550
And then secondly
around exchanges

00:57:58.550 --> 00:58:01.400
the concepts of
pre-trade transparency,

00:58:01.400 --> 00:58:05.420
post-trade transparency,
trying to bring transparency

00:58:05.420 --> 00:58:08.610
and saying we're going to
promote economic activity.

00:58:08.610 --> 00:58:11.600
So in the US, there were
two laws passed in 1933

00:58:11.600 --> 00:58:15.722
and '34, the Exchange Act and--

00:58:15.722 --> 00:58:17.930
sorry, I'm going to have to
remember-- the Securities

00:58:17.930 --> 00:58:18.972
Act and the Exchange Act.

00:58:18.972 --> 00:58:21.470
But one was for issuers,
which was the first one,

00:58:21.470 --> 00:58:25.490
and the second was for
exchanges in '33 and '34.

00:58:25.490 --> 00:58:28.140
And I think those
are the key things.

00:58:28.140 --> 00:58:30.050
Let me just mention--
the key question,

00:58:30.050 --> 00:58:31.850
the definition that
we will be wrestling

00:58:31.850 --> 00:58:34.070
with for the next
several weeks is

00:58:34.070 --> 00:58:37.310
when is something is security,
when is it a commodity, when

00:58:37.310 --> 00:58:39.080
is it a derivative.

00:58:39.080 --> 00:58:42.530
We don't have to answer these
today, but those will be--

00:58:42.530 --> 00:58:43.890
is it a security?

00:58:43.890 --> 00:58:45.050
Is it a commodity?

00:58:45.050 --> 00:58:47.280
Is it a derivative?

00:58:47.280 --> 00:58:51.360
Not only are there
different laws for each,

00:58:51.360 --> 00:58:53.370
but there's different
public policies

00:58:53.370 --> 00:58:57.240
and different normative
behavior that's implicated.

00:58:57.240 --> 00:59:00.540
Securities are when
there is an issuer.

00:59:00.540 --> 00:59:03.150
And fundamentally, just from
a public policy point of view,

00:59:03.150 --> 00:59:06.210
there's an
information asymmetry.

00:59:06.210 --> 00:59:09.060
That person raising money
knows more information

00:59:09.060 --> 00:59:12.750
than the person investing,
they probably always will.

00:59:12.750 --> 00:59:17.085
So you get to, what's the
fair exchange of information?

00:59:19.500 --> 00:59:21.000
I'm going to skip
a couple of things

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:24.660
just to say why investor
protection to Kyle's question.

00:59:24.660 --> 00:59:25.560
It goes beyond.

00:59:25.560 --> 00:59:29.790
And here are what are the Gary
Gensler four bullet points.

00:59:29.790 --> 00:59:32.310
This you will not see
in a textbook somewhere.

00:59:32.310 --> 00:59:35.040
But these are the key things
I think investor protection

00:59:35.040 --> 00:59:37.490
layers on top of
consumer protection.

00:59:37.490 --> 00:59:40.710
One, investors get full
and fair disclosure.

00:59:40.710 --> 00:59:43.530
You can debate what full
and fair disclosure is,

00:59:43.530 --> 00:59:46.080
but it's something
more than I'm selling

00:59:46.080 --> 00:59:47.280
you this carton of milk.

00:59:49.960 --> 00:59:53.710
Fraud and deceptive
practices are prohibited.

00:59:53.710 --> 00:59:55.660
Now, fraud is supposedly
prohibited even

00:59:55.660 --> 00:59:57.760
when you buy a carton
of milk, but there's

00:59:57.760 --> 01:00:00.010
some added bits to it.

01:00:00.010 --> 01:00:02.770
And then this thing I said
about the secondary markets,

01:00:02.770 --> 01:00:05.330
promoting price transparency.

01:00:05.330 --> 01:00:07.300
And then lastly one that
I hadn't talked about,

01:00:07.300 --> 01:00:10.750
that the advisors usually
have a lot of conflicts

01:00:10.750 --> 01:00:12.342
in the financial markets.

01:00:12.342 --> 01:00:14.050
There's almost always,
in most countries,

01:00:14.050 --> 01:00:17.710
some additional responsibilities
around the advisors,

01:00:17.710 --> 01:00:20.350
whether it's what's called
a fiduciary responsibility

01:00:20.350 --> 01:00:22.450
or some other responsibility.

01:00:22.450 --> 01:00:25.000
Sometimes, it's
just a best efforts,

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:28.660
but there's usually some
additional responsibilities

01:00:28.660 --> 01:00:29.980
on advisors.

01:00:29.980 --> 01:00:31.930
And those four bullet points--

01:00:31.930 --> 01:00:34.810
I don't mean to teach
a whole securities law

01:00:34.810 --> 01:00:37.090
course in three minutes
or less, but those

01:00:37.090 --> 01:00:38.560
are how I quite summarize it.

01:00:38.560 --> 01:00:39.060
Tom?

01:00:39.060 --> 01:00:40.560
AUDIENCE: That first
bullet, is that

01:00:40.560 --> 01:00:43.750
from insurers or from issuers?

01:00:43.750 --> 01:00:45.490
GARY GENSLER: Issuers.

01:00:45.490 --> 01:00:46.630
Thank you.

01:00:46.630 --> 01:00:49.240
Issuers, yes.

01:00:49.240 --> 01:00:49.857
Sorry.

01:00:49.857 --> 01:00:50.357
Emily?

01:00:50.357 --> 01:00:51.857
AUDIENCE: Is there
any consideration

01:00:51.857 --> 01:00:57.340
for how to prioritize
between investor and consumer

01:00:57.340 --> 01:01:00.310
protection versus,
say, tax enforcement?

01:01:00.310 --> 01:01:04.020
In that I can imagine that if
there was increased protection,

01:01:04.020 --> 01:01:05.710
it would incentivize
more investment,

01:01:05.710 --> 01:01:09.850
which then could, without
prior tax coverage,

01:01:09.850 --> 01:01:11.310
make it so that [INAUDIBLE].

01:01:11.310 --> 01:01:13.407
GARY GENSLER: Is that
word tax or hacks?

01:01:13.407 --> 01:01:13.990
AUDIENCE: Tax.

01:01:13.990 --> 01:01:14.823
GARY GENSLER: T-A-X.

01:01:14.823 --> 01:01:15.958
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:01:15.958 --> 01:01:18.250
So I would imagine that more
protection would encourage

01:01:18.250 --> 01:01:20.560
more investment, but then
more people potentially

01:01:20.560 --> 01:01:24.100
would be evading taxes
if there wasn't already

01:01:24.100 --> 01:01:27.620
that tax framework in place.

01:01:27.620 --> 01:01:30.690
GARY GENSLER: So Emily
raises the question,

01:01:30.690 --> 01:01:32.550
how does any
society, in a sense,

01:01:32.550 --> 01:01:37.500
make some trade-offs between
tax and investor protection

01:01:37.500 --> 01:01:40.080
regimes?

01:01:40.080 --> 01:01:42.840
And ultimately, if I can
take it one step back,

01:01:42.840 --> 01:01:44.800
that's what some
countries are doing now,

01:01:44.800 --> 01:01:47.370
but they've been doing it
for a couple of centuries.

01:01:47.370 --> 01:01:49.260
How do you promote
innovation that might

01:01:49.260 --> 01:01:51.140
promote economic activity?

01:01:51.140 --> 01:01:53.730
So I'm broadening your question.

01:01:53.730 --> 01:01:56.500
How do you promote
economic activity

01:01:56.500 --> 01:01:59.820
while in the midst still
promoting whatever social goods

01:01:59.820 --> 01:02:04.260
you're trying to achieve in
some regulatory framework?

01:02:04.260 --> 01:02:06.360
Investor protection,
so I made it

01:02:06.360 --> 01:02:10.290
the broadest, because that's
what you'll hear often

01:02:10.290 --> 01:02:11.690
around blockchain and Bitcoin.

01:02:11.690 --> 01:02:13.920
But it was true when the
railroads came along.

01:02:13.920 --> 01:02:17.370
It was true more recently
when the internet came along,

01:02:17.370 --> 01:02:19.170
how to promote
this new technology

01:02:19.170 --> 01:02:23.100
of the internet while actually
still promoting broadly

01:02:23.100 --> 01:02:26.420
the social goods that
we're trying to achieve.

01:02:26.420 --> 01:02:30.110
I'm one in the camp
that says protecting

01:02:30.110 --> 01:02:32.870
against illicit activity,
financial stability

01:02:32.870 --> 01:02:37.640
of investor protection
do, in and of themselves,

01:02:37.640 --> 01:02:41.060
promote society and
economic well-being.

01:02:41.060 --> 01:02:43.910
I don't think-- this
is Gary Gensler.

01:02:43.910 --> 01:02:46.610
I don't think they're
necessarily in conflict.

01:02:46.610 --> 01:02:49.430
There are others who
say no, no, no, no, you

01:02:49.430 --> 01:02:52.850
can't promote economic
activity or taxes

01:02:52.850 --> 01:02:57.040
and also promote
investor protection.

01:02:57.040 --> 01:02:59.150
I believe that's
more short sighted.

01:02:59.150 --> 01:03:02.650
I think the regimes and reforms
of the 1930s in this country

01:03:02.650 --> 01:03:04.150
and other decades
in other countries

01:03:04.150 --> 01:03:08.590
are part of why we have had
such a prosperous last 70 or 80

01:03:08.590 --> 01:03:09.850
years.

01:03:09.850 --> 01:03:11.500
That investor
protection actually

01:03:11.500 --> 01:03:15.910
lowers the risk to issuers.

01:03:15.910 --> 01:03:18.670
Thank you for
correcting, issuers.

01:03:18.670 --> 01:03:22.810
It lowers the risk of issuers
and lowers the cost of capital.

01:03:22.810 --> 01:03:25.850
If you have good
investor protection,

01:03:25.850 --> 01:03:32.220
I believe ultimately it
lowers the cost of capital,

01:03:32.220 --> 01:03:34.640
which is what I said and
those two bullet points.

01:03:34.640 --> 01:03:36.650
So US securities
law, did anybody

01:03:36.650 --> 01:03:38.510
want to tell me what
the Howey test was?

01:03:41.100 --> 01:03:44.610
What are those
arches right there?

01:03:44.610 --> 01:03:47.120
Well, we'll take somebody new.

01:03:47.120 --> 01:03:49.304
First name?

01:03:49.304 --> 01:03:51.200
AUDIENCE: Actually,
the Howey Test

01:03:51.200 --> 01:03:57.810
is coming from a Supreme
Court case which was in 1946.

01:03:57.810 --> 01:04:00.860
And at that time,
the Supreme Court

01:04:00.860 --> 01:04:04.520
was about to make a decision
on, as far as I remember,

01:04:04.520 --> 01:04:06.640
citrus groves.

01:04:06.640 --> 01:04:11.090
And at the end of the day,
they decided that citrus groves

01:04:11.090 --> 01:04:12.800
are securities.

01:04:12.800 --> 01:04:17.800
And right after that,
there's a kind of agreement

01:04:17.800 --> 01:04:21.140
to be able to define
something as a security.

01:04:21.140 --> 01:04:23.790
It has to meet four criteria.

01:04:23.790 --> 01:04:25.290
GARY GENSLER: Let's
pause you there.

01:04:25.290 --> 01:04:25.940
All right.

01:04:25.940 --> 01:04:28.730
So citrus groves
in Florida somehow

01:04:28.730 --> 01:04:30.410
are securities,
absolutely right.

01:04:30.410 --> 01:04:33.890
A man named William Howey,
he ran for governor actually

01:04:33.890 --> 01:04:35.610
in Florida a couple
of times and lost,

01:04:35.610 --> 01:04:39.140
but he had a real estate
venture and he had those arches

01:04:39.140 --> 01:04:41.360
by his real estate venture.

01:04:41.360 --> 01:04:44.600
And he figured he could
sell part of his land

01:04:44.600 --> 01:04:46.310
as citrus groves.

01:04:46.310 --> 01:04:49.370
So the question was, when he
was selling that land could that

01:04:49.370 --> 01:04:53.510
be, actually technically
an investment contract?

01:04:53.510 --> 01:04:57.140
Because in 1933, the
Congress of the United States

01:04:57.140 --> 01:04:59.660
included in the
definition of security

01:04:59.660 --> 01:05:03.730
these two words,
investment contract.

01:05:03.730 --> 01:05:06.850
It said equity, stock, options.

01:05:06.850 --> 01:05:08.750
It kept having a
bunch of commas.

01:05:08.750 --> 01:05:11.630
There was a comma,
investment contract, comma,

01:05:11.630 --> 01:05:12.830
and it kept going.

01:05:12.830 --> 01:05:15.230
So the real legal question
that went to the Supreme Court

01:05:15.230 --> 01:05:20.540
was not whether Bill Howey's
citrus groves were securities.

01:05:20.540 --> 01:05:24.920
It was whether Bill Howey's
citrus groves were investment

01:05:24.920 --> 01:05:26.930
contracts, because
Congress had already

01:05:26.930 --> 01:05:30.890
decided by putting the two
words and a couple of columns

01:05:30.890 --> 01:05:32.330
that it was a security.

01:05:32.330 --> 01:05:34.760
And that separates us
from the European Union

01:05:34.760 --> 01:05:37.820
and many other jurisdictions,
because Congress

01:05:37.820 --> 01:05:41.240
put those two words in there,
investment contracts, which

01:05:41.240 --> 01:05:43.250
had to do with a lot
of scams and frauds

01:05:43.250 --> 01:05:47.530
from the 1890s to the 1920s.

01:05:47.530 --> 01:05:51.730
And to meet the
investment contract test

01:05:51.730 --> 01:05:53.560
is this for part test.

01:05:53.560 --> 01:05:56.980
Is it an investment
of money or assets?

01:05:56.980 --> 01:06:02.030
Basically, the SEC has said
that if you're giving Ether--

01:06:02.030 --> 01:06:04.190
or you're giving
Bitcoin to buy Ether,

01:06:04.190 --> 01:06:11.330
you're giving Bitcoin to buy
some Amanda token, all right?

01:06:11.330 --> 01:06:13.580
That's an investment
of money or assets.

01:06:13.580 --> 01:06:14.900
That's what the SEC has said.

01:06:14.900 --> 01:06:17.810
And most lawyers kind
of agree with that.

01:06:17.810 --> 01:06:20.810
Is it an investment in
a common enterprise?

01:06:20.810 --> 01:06:25.840
So is there a group
of developers that--

01:06:25.840 --> 01:06:28.230
or is this like a
common enterprise?

01:06:28.230 --> 01:06:29.610
Some people debate that.

01:06:29.610 --> 01:06:31.650
Some people say, well,
we weren't-- really,

01:06:31.650 --> 01:06:32.640
it's an open source.

01:06:32.640 --> 01:06:34.320
If you're an open
source software,

01:06:34.320 --> 01:06:36.030
that's not going to
be enough to get away

01:06:36.030 --> 01:06:39.070
from being a common enterprise.

01:06:39.070 --> 01:06:41.830
Is there a reasonable
expectation of profits?

01:06:41.830 --> 01:06:45.050
